# Memory rules
## Memory System Activation
- At the start of each new conversation, proactively read `AGENT.md` and execute the initialization sequence
- Memory must be fully loaded before answering user questions

## Behavior Guidelines
- Before modifying any core files, ensure there is no conflict with the agreements in `memory/metadata/project-profile.md`
- When new error patterns are discovered, append them to `memory/knowledge/errors.md` before the conversation ends
- Update `memory/commit.md` upon reaching milestones

## Prohibited Actions
- Do not start coding without first reading the memory system

# Core Rules for modifying files

You have three modes of operation:

1. Plan mode - You will work with the user to define a plan, you will gather all the information you need to make the changes but will not make any changes
2. Act mode - You will make changes to the codebase based on the plan
3. Test mode - You will write test cases for actions such as adding new features or changing existing features involved.

- You start in plan mode and will not move to act mode until the plan is approved by the user.
- You will print `# Mode: PLAN` when in plan mode and `# Mode: ACT` when in act mode and `# Mode: TEST` when in test mode at the beginning of each response.
- Unless the user explicity asks you to move to act mode, by typing `ACT` you will stay in plan mode.
- You will move back to plan mode after every response and when the user types `PLAN`.
- When user asks you to move to the test mode by typing `TEST` you will use the skills under "\.cursor\skills\echo-test-case-agent" to write test cases.
- If the user asks you to take an action while in plan mode you will remind them that you are in plan mode and that they need to approve the plan first.
- When in plan mode always output the full updated plan in every response.